%S A394749 0,1,1,1,1,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,3,2,1,3,1,2,3,2,1,4,1,2,3,4,1,3,1,4,3,2,5,
%T A394749 4,1,2,3,5,1,3,1,4,5,2,1,6,1,5,3,4,1,6,5,4,3,2,1,6,1,2,7,4,5,6,1,4,3,
%U A394749 7,1,6,1,2,5,4,7,6,1,8,3,2,1,7,5,2,3
%N A394749 Largest GCD of the digits of n in any base b < n, considering only cases where all digits are nonzero.
%C A394749 For n >= 2, n base n always equals {1, 0}, which is always excluded from consideration because it includes a digit of 0.
%C A394749 For n >= 3, n base n-1 always equals {1, 1}, so a(n) always equals at least 1.
%C A394749 If n+1 is a square, a(n) is a record high term sqrt(n+1)-1, because the digits of n base sqrt(n+1) are {sqrt(n+1)-1, sqrt(n+1)-1}.
%C A394749 For n >= 3, a(n) is always a divisor of n; a(n) = 1 for all prime n (A000040) and all squares of prime n (A001248).
%C A394749 For n >= 10 which is a product of 2 distinct primes (A006881), a(n) equals the smaller of the 2 prime factors.
%C A394749 Including cases with digits of 0 (which do not discount the GCD) gives A060775 for n >= 2.
%H A394749 Charles L. Hohn, <a href="/A394749/b394749.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%e A394749 n <= 2 produce no examples with all nonzero digits, so a(2) = 0.
%e A394749 a(3) = 1 because the digits of 3 base 2 are {1, 1} which has a GCD of 1, and this is the only applicable case for n = 3.
%e A394749 a(42) = 3 because the digits of 42 base 11 are {3, 9} which has a GCD of 3, and no other base <= 42 produces all nonzero digits with a larger GCD.
%o A394749 (PARI) a(n)={my(m=0); for(b=2, n-1, my(d=digits(n, b)); if(vecmin(d), m=max(m, gcd(d)))); m}
%o A394749 (Python)
%o A394749 from math import gcd
%o A394749 from sympy.ntheory import digits
%o A394749 def A394749(n): return max(gcd(*s) for b in range(2,n) if 0 not in (s:=digits(n,b)[1:])) if n>2 else 0 # _Chai Wah Wu_, Apr 07 2026
%Y A394749 Cf. A060775, A000040, A001248, A006881.
%K A394749 nonn,base
%O A394749 2,7
%A A394749 _Charles L. Hohn_, Mar 31 2026
